Bonnie Raitt was actually a legend before she ever became a star. She spent the ‘70s and ‘80s mixing folk, blues, soul, and rock, and she could put a fresh face on Robert Johnson's “Walking Blues” with her jumping, urgent version or tug on your tear ducts with her soulful slant on the John Prine ballad “Angel from Montgomery.” With a rep as a roots music master in her back pocket, she went on to achieve mainstream success in the early ‘90s with hits like the slinky, sultry soul-rocker “Something to Talk About” and the heartbreaking, country-tinged “I Can't Make You Love Me.”

Eclectic alternative rock band Cake caught on in the ‘90s with a blend of funk, garage rock, lounge music, country, and whatever else inspired them at any given moment. Like fellow genre-benders They Might Be Giants and Ween, Cake arrived at their post-punk sound via the distinct musical personalities within the band, such as the literary deadpan sarcasm of John McCrea's vocal, and Vince DiFiore's mariachi-esque trumpet lines. Predictably unpredictable, the band never stopped winning over mainstream rock fans, especially with 2001's <I>Comfort Eagle.
Ed Sheeran: Songs I Play in My Car

Like many of us, Ed Sheeran does a lot of his very best music listening in the car. So when we asked the record-blitzing singer-songwriter if he’d mind putting together an exclusive playlist, we were thrilled to receive a brand-new, handcrafted, road-ready set. Particularly because the music Ed’s selected is so diverse: You’ll hear irresistible UK rap bops from artists like Aitch and AJ Tracey nestle up against Mahalia and Khalid’s slinky R&B and breakthrough singer-songwriter magic from Maisie Peters and Lewis Capaldi. It’s an eclecticism present in his bold new album, No.6 Collaborations Project, so buckle up and enjoy the ride.

Dave Grohl was best known as Nirvana's drummer, but it didn't take long for him to show the music world that he can do it all. After recording the Foo Fighters' eponymous debut on his own, Grohl fleshed out the project with musicians like Nate Mendel and Pat Smear. The Foos went on to release a post-grunge classic in 1997's The Color and the Shape that established them as alt-rock staples, and they haven't slowed down since. With a bevy of GRAMMY®-winning hits to their name, the Foos have proven through the decades that a classic alt-rock formula eschews trends and can't be imitated.

Few artists changed the musical landscape like James Marshall Hendrix. Working with both The Jimi Hendrix Experience and Band of Gypsys, the guitarist's run of classic albums between 1967 and 1970 offered a revolutionary fusion of blues, funk, and psychedelic rock. His feedback-drenched performances stunned contemporaries like Eric Clapton and Jeff Beck, and he became notorious for his showmanship, ending many of his concerts with his guitar engulfed in flames. Decades after his tragically early death, Hendrix's songs remain jaw-dropping, and his skill as a guitarist remains unmatched.

From her 1978 debut smash "Wuthering Heights" onwards, Kate Bush was a critical darling whose records also caught the ear of the greater record-buying public, at least in her native Britain. Her early adoption of the Fairlight CMI sampler gave '80s albums The Dreaming and Hounds of Love an endearingly eccentric edge that broadened her appeal among adventurous American ears as well. After the mature The Sensual World and The Red Shoes, Bush took an extended break until 2005's Aerial. In 2014, she surprised fans with her first live performances in 35 years.

Paul Simon and Art Garfunkel grew up together as elementary school friends. They began playing music together in the late-‘50s as the musical duo Tom and Jerry, but parted ways to attend college. The pair were later reunited in the folk scene of ‘60s Greenwich Village, and released their debut, Wednesday Morning, 3 A.M. in 1964. By 1966, they found success with the album Sounds of Silence, which solidified their status and began their cascade of hit records including three studio albums and the soundtrack to the film The Graduate.

Stevie Ray Vaughan achieved guitar-hero status by combining the grittiness of his blues roots with the wild adventurousness of his hero, Jimi Hendrix. Growing up a musical prodigy in Texas, the young Vaughan was gigging professionally when he was still a teenager. He started playing with his faithful rhythm section, Double Trouble, in the late '70s, and by the '80s, was working as a studio guitarist for the likes of David Bowie and James Brown. Tragically, Vaughan died in a helicopter crash in 1990 at the age of 35, but his reputation as a rock legend was already secure.

With earthy, instantly catchy tunes that capture the promise of wide-open horizons and youthful rebellion, Tom Petty forever changed the course of rock 'n' roll. Although he skillfully adapted over four decades—mellowing slightly from the sneering intensity of mid-‘70s albums with The Heartbreakers to the shimmering acoustic beauty of Wildflowers—Petty's chiming guitars and gift for sing-at-the-top-of-your-lungs choruses are a constant. But something about Petty's music is also so quintessentially American—whether he's inspired by the surreal life of sunny Hollywood or the lure of the highway—that he's one of the most universally appealing voices on the FM dial.
